How can I fix this Java code to avoid a ConcurrentModificationException when iterating over a list and removing some elements? "import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.List;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<Integer> numbers = new ArrayList<>();
        numbers.add(1);
        numbers.add(2);
        numbers.add(3);
        numbers.add(4);
        numbers.add(5);

        for (Integer n : numbers) {
            if (n % 2 == 0) {
                numbers.remove(n);
            }
        }

        System.out.println(numbers);
    }
}"

answer:
The above code will throw a ConcurrentModificationException (CME) if anything else accesses the list while the loop is running. The CME happens because numbers is a list and lists are not thread safe. The list is modified in-place by the loop, which means that another thread can see the updated list but the loop is not finished yet. This is a common problem with Java lists. To fix the issue, you can make a copy of the list before iterating over it:

"import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.List;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<Integer> numbers = new ArrayList<>();
        numbers.add(1);
        numbers.add(2);
        numbers.add(3);
        numbers.add(4);
        numbers.add(5);

        List<Integer> copy = new ArrayList<>(numbers);
        for (Integer n : copy) {
            if (n % 2 == 0) {
                numbers.remove(n);
            }
        }

        System.out.println(numbers);
    }
}"

The above code will not throw a CME.

