        String name = args != null && args.length > 0 ? args[0] : null;
        System.out.println(name.length());
    }
}"

George is unlikely to succeed in his claim because Frank did not act with malice. To establish defamation, George must prove the following elements:
1. That Frank published a statement;
2. That the statement was defamatory;
3. That Frank knew the statement was false or did not care if it was false; and
4. That George suffered harm as a result of the statement.

Frank did not act with malice because he did not know the allegations he made in the article about George were false. George may have information to back up his claims, but Frank is under no obligation to reveal his sources. To be considered defamatory, the statement must be false and it must be communicated to a third party. Here, the statement was that George was involved in a corruption scandal and that he had an affair with his secretary. These claims are all factual and can be proven true or false. If George was not involved in the corruption scandal and he did not have an affair with his secretary, Frank would not have defamed George.
